<F P=100> PRC MEDIA ON TAIWAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Possesses `No Optimism' for ARATS-SEF Meeting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2503183894 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0836 
GMT 25 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2503183894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, 25 Mar (XINHUA) -- Based on the common 
understanding reached this February between the Association for 
Relations Across the Taiwan Strait [ARATS] and Taiwan's Straits 
Exchange Foundation [SEF] in the "Joint Press Release of Tang 
Shubei and Jiao Renhe," the two organizations will began holding 
their fourth working level talks today on issues that include 
the fishery dispute between the two sides of the Strait. 
However, due to moves by Taiwan prior to its delegates' 
departure for Beijing to "veto part of the Tang-Jiao common 
understanding," there is no optimism for reaching an agreement 
during the current talks. 
  At the conclusion of the Tang-Jiao talks this February, 
Taiwan described the "Joint Press Release" as a having developed 
a "great degree of common understanding" between the two sides. 
Huang Kunhui, chairman of the "Mainland Affairs Council [MAC]," 
and others gave it a "high degree of affirmation." However, 
according to Taiwan press reports, part of the common 
understanding reached during the Tang-Jiao talks was vetoed in 
mid-March during a meeting convened by MAC, and attended by such 
as the "National Security Bureau [NSB]" and "Ministry of Justice 
[MOJ]," to discuss strategies to be adopted at the forthcoming 
fourth round of talks between the two organizations. This 
caused "great shock" among the SEF delegates to the talks. 
Complying with a top SEF official's request, "MAC" called a 
special meeting again on 19 March. However, departments such as 
"NSB" and "MOJ" again made firm demands for rights, including 
jurisdiction over judicial matters," thus "overturning the 
important common understanding over the three issues formed 
during the Tang-Jiao talks." They also claimed they wanted to 
"maintain the bottom line of the two organizations' Taibei 
[Taipei] talks on the premise of giving consideration to the 
dignity of the rights of jurisdiction over legal matters." 
  Commenting on this, the Taiwan press noted that by 
overturning the common understanding reached in the Tang-Jiao 
talks, Taiwan will cast variables in reaching an agreement 
during the two organizations' fourth round of talks and will 
create pre-talks tension. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

