<F P=100> PRC MEDIA ON TAIWAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry To Restrict Future Hong Kong, Macao Investment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK0803123794 Hong Kong ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE in Chinese 0910 
GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK0803123794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Taiwan Businessmen's Investment in Hong Kong, Macao After </F>
1997, 1999 Will Be Restricted" -- ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE headline] 
  [Text] Hong Kong, 7 Mar (ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE) -- A report 
from Taipei: According to the provisions of the "Draft 
Regulations on Relations With Hong Kong and Macao," which is 
being examined by the Mainland Affairs Council of the 
Administrative Yuan of Taiwan, the "reporting for the record" 
system will be adopted for the people of Taiwan to invest in 
Hong Kong and Macao after 1997 and 1999, respectively. The 
Ministry of Economy will promulgate regulations restricting 
investment in Hong Kong and Macao by enterprises on the island. 
Any offender will be fined from NT$300,000 to NT$3 million [New 
Taiwan dollars] and such punishment can be repeated. 
  In addition, the Mainland Affairs Council also has examined 
many relevant regulations, the main content of which includes 
the following: Taiwan's financial organizations may continue to 
accept and exchange Hong Kong dollars on condition that the Hong 
Kong dollars have "ample exchange reserves" and can be 
"exchanged freely." 
  Regarding transportation, the Mainland Affairs Council said 
that "with permission," Taiwan's ships and civilian aircraft 
"can navigate between Taiwan, Hong Kong, and Macao." The 
procedures for obtaining permission will be formulated by the 
Ministry of Communications. With permission, ships and aircraft 
of Hong Kong and Macao also may enter Taiwan's restricted and 
prohibited waters and aviation information areas. With 
permission, foreign ships and aircraft also may navigate between 
Taiwan, Hong Kong, and Macao. 
  Taiwan's Mainland Affairs Council is scheduled to complete 
all preliminary examination work on 7 March and to make public 
these drafts to extensively solicit the views and suggestions of 
various circles on the island. At the same time, it has planned 
to entrust academic organizations with holding seminars in Hong 
Kong and Macao to listen to views on the legislation of various 
circles in Hong Kong and Macao. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

