<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Taipei Radio Says Cross-Strait Talks Remain `Deadlocked' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2803122094 Taipei Voice of Free China in English 0200 GMT 
28 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2803122094 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei Voice of Free China </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "News" program] </F>
  [Text] The cross-strait talk between Taiwan's Strait 
Exchange Foundation [SEF] and its mainland counterpart remained 
deadlocked in Peking [Beijing] on Sunday [27 March]. On the 
agenda were talks on the repatriation of hijackers, illegal 
immigrants, and the settlement of fishery disputes in the Taiwan 
Strait. However, bickering was the common point throughout the 
negotiation, according to local media reports. 
  Sun Yafu, the chief negotiator for the Association for 
Relations Across the Taiwan Strait [ARATS], accused Taipei of 
swallowing promises made during the previous round of talks in 
February. He said SEF Secretary General Chao Jen-ho had 
verbally agreed that hijackers would not be legally viewed as 
criminal suspects when they were repatriated. However, SEF 
Deputy Secretary and Taipei's chief negotiator H.Y. Hsu [Hsu 
Hui-yu] said that ARATS was confused over what Chao had said and 
that Taipei would recognize only promises written in black and 
white. Hsu claimed that the mainland delegation had been 
insincere throughout the talks. 

</TEXT>

