<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Li Peng Chairs State Council's 16th Executive Meeting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2503234994 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 1030 
GMT 25 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2503234994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, 25 Mar (XINHUA) -- Premier Li Peng today 
chaired the 16th executive meeting of the State Council at which 
"China's Agenda 21," or the "White Paper on China's Population, 
Environment, and Development in the 21st Century," was discussed 
and approved. 
  The problems of population, environment, and development 
have 
drawn attention from various countries in the world in recent 
years. To counter the global economic, social, resources, and 
environmental problems, the Chinese Government took the lead in 
initiating and convening a ministerial conference on environment 
and development of developing countries in Beijing in June 1991. 
In June 1992, the UN held an environment and development summit 
in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil and adopted the "Rio Declaration on 
Environment and Development," the "Agenda 21," and other 
documents. Premier Li Peng attended the summit and, on behalf 
of the Chinese Government, promised to fulfill the "Agenda 21" 
and other documents. According to this commitment, 52 
departments under the State Council, including the State 
Planning Commission and the State Science and Technology 
Commission, jointly worked out "China's Agenda 21," or the 
"White Paper on China's Population, Environment, and Development 
in the 21st Century." In line with China's basic conditions and 
development strategy, the document sets the general strategy, 
policy, and measures for the coordinated and sustainable 
development of economy, society, resources, environment, 
population, and education. It will become a guiding document 
for China in making its long and mid-term plans for national 
economic and social development and will form important goals 
and contents of the Ninth Five-Year Plan and the 2010 program. 
Meanwhile, the document has also demonstrated the Chinese 
Government's actual action and principled position in earnestly 
implementing the "Agenda 21." 
  The meeting also discussed and adopted, in principle, the 
"(Draft) Outline Program of the State Industrial Policies for 
the 1990s." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

