<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Control Raw Silk Prices </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK2703053694 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in English 0501 GMT 
26 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK2703053694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 26 (CNS) -- From March 25 this year, 
prices for purchasing raw silk in China are controlled at RMB 
[Renminbi] 180,000 per tonne with only 10 percent floating 
prices being permitted and no purchasing at prices of over RMB 
200,000 for each tonne will be permitted, a top official of the 
China Silk Import and Export Corporation (CSIEC) recently 
announced here. 
  Since the beginning of this year, a soaring rise in prices 
for silk and silk cloth materials have been seen with prices of 
raw silk, rising by 25 percent between January and March. The 
skyrocketing prices for raw silk, besides the reduction of the 
silkworm cocoon production last year and the drop in storage of 
such materials, were mainly caused by artificial factors with 
speculation by middlemen being very rampant in the country as 
they took advantage of the situation to hold back supplies and 
so raise prices, posing a heavy burden on silk-related textile 
and printing and dyeing mills and threatening the silk industry 
in the country and the preeminent place China has had in the 
international silk market for a long time. 
  The CSIEC, the state authorized company in charge of 
administration and management in this sector, will consequently 
coordinate its branches at provincial levels in practising 
management with price limitations over the raw silk market. 
  According to a leader of the CSIEC, if the country fails to 
put the sharply rising prices of raw silk under control, the 
outcome will be very serious and another "silkworm cocoon war" 
will break out. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

