<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Massive' Overseas Purchasing Plan Revealed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK2703020494 Beijing CHINA DAILY in English 25 Mar 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> HK2703020494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing CHINA DAILY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Wu Yunhe: "Government Reveals Foreign Shopping List"] </F>
  [Text] The government is expected to launch a massive 
overseas purchasing programme to back up the nation's 
modernization drive over the next seven years according to 
official sources. 
  The programme, drafted by the State Planning Commission, 
involves importing advanced technology and equipment valued at 
some $30 billion. 
  A large part of the new technology will be used to develop 
24 
key agricultural projects during the 1994-2000 period. 
  However, the $30 billion buying list also covers other 
sectors, including energy, machinery and electronics, chemicals, 
transportation, metallurgy and post and telecommunications. 
  The money to support the immense purchase will come mainly 
from State foreign exchange reserves and the financial coffers 
of relevant departments and local governments -- in addition to 
overseas commercial credits and soft loans from foreign 
governments and international financial institutions, government 
officials said. 
  The agricultural technology and equipment will be used for 
projects across China, including Guangdong, Hainan, Fujian, 
Henan, Sichuan, Jiangsu, Hebei, Liaoning and Gansu Provinces and 
the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region. 
  The key agricultural projects will focus on integrating 
farming, animal husbandry, fisheries and forestry with 
processing and environmental protection in the grain-rich Henan, 
Sichuan, Fujian, Hainan, Jilin Provinces and the Liaohe River 
region of Liaoning Province. 
  Also high on the agenda are vital irrigation projects such 
as 
the delta projects for the Yellow River, Huaihe and Haihe 
Rivers; the irrigation programme of the southen Xinjiang Uygur 
Autonomous Region; the Tongyu River irrigation engineering 
project in Jiangsu Province; and the farmland irrigation project 
in Hubei and Hunan provinces. 
  The imported technology will also be introduced to help 
State 
farms in Guangdong Province develop tropical crops. The Bohai 
Bay aquaculture project and the national agricultural-technology 
popularization programme are also targeted for imports. 
  Other recipients will include the compound-fodder project; 
the grain storage, transportation and market development 
project; and the second-stage afforestation project. 
  Additionally, the programme covers the ongoing Taihu Lake 
flood-protection project in Jiangsu Province; the second-stage 
red-soil development project in South China; and the Loess 
Plateau soil-erosion protection and agricultural development 
project of Northwest China. 
  Finally, part of the imported techniques and equipment will 
be used for the nationwide seed-breeding development project; 
agricultural development along the Hexi Corridor in Gansu 
Province; and poverty alleviation programmes in Guizhou and 
Yunnan Provinces and the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

