<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bank Regulations on Foreign Exchange Promulgated </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2603164494 Beijing XINHUA in English 1550 GMT 26 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2603164494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 26 (XINHUA) -- An official from the 
People's Bank of China said here today that the provisional 
regulations on the exchange settlement, surrender and payment 
have been formulated to ensure an ample supply of foreign 
exchange by the central bank in order to realize the 
convertibility of renminbi under current accounts, which is 
central to the reform of China's financial system. 
  The regulations were issued on December 29, 1993. 
  According to the regulations, all foreign exchange receipts, 
except those held by foreign-funded enterprises, foreign loans 
and foreign exchange for debt servicing and exchanges in the 
hands of individuals, must be surrendered to the state banks and 
if they need foreign exchange for import and export and other 
purposes, they have to buy it in the exchange market. 
  The regulations say that foreign-funded enterprises may 
retain their foreign exchange receipts. They may sell or buy 
them at the foreign exchange swap market. 

</TEXT>

