<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   Depositary Receipts for Firm Enter U.S. Market </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2903002294 Beijing XINHUA in English 2251 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2903002294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] New York, March 28 (XINHUA) -- The American 
Depositary Receipts (ADRS) for Shanghai Chlor-Alkali Chemical 
Co., Ltd have started trading in the United States, according to 
Xu Rxongyi, chairman of the company here today. 
  "We believe that the potential for our company is enormous," 
Xu told a group of reporters at the Bank of New York, which has 
been selected to act as the depositary for the sponsored level-1 
ADRS of the Shanghai company. 
  The Bank of New York announced on March 21 that Shanghai 
Chlor- Alkali Chemical Company's ADRS were effective and are 
traded in the ratio of one ADR representing ten "B" shares 
traded on Shanghai Stock Exchange. 
  They will trade on the over-the-counter market in the United 
States. 
  The Shanghai company, a Sino-foreign joint stock company 
established in July 1992, produces over 20 kinds of products 
with over 40 different styles of four categories. 
  With the capacity to produce 350,000 tons of caustic soda 
and 
220,000 tons of PVC [polyvinyl chloride], the company's products 
have been exported to over ten countries and regions, such as 
Japan, the United States and Italy. 
  Shanghai Chlor-Alkali's B shares owned by foreign investors 
now represent 34.9 percent of its total shares outstanding. In 
1993, based on international accounting standards, the company's 
total sales were 1.3 billion Chinese yuan and profit after tax 
was 171 million yuan. 
  According to Wu Yalun, vice chairman of the Shanghai Stock 
Exchange, Shanghai Chlor-Alkali now became the third Chinese 
company to have ADRS traded at the U.S. market. He expected 
that there would be more Chinese ADRS to enter the U.S. capital 
market if they perform well. 

</TEXT>

