<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Report on Jiang Zemin Meeting Kim Yong-sam </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2803060894 Seoul YONHAP in English 0506 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2803060894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 28 (YONHAP) -- South Korean President 
Kim Yong-sam and First Lady Son Myong-sun arrived at the Great 
Hall of the People Saturday morning amid a 21-gun salute 
accorded to guests of the state. 
  "It's nice to see you again," Kim said to Chinese President 
Jiang Zemin, recounting their first meeting in Seattle last 
November during the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) 
summit. 
  "You came a long way," Jiang answered, taking Kim's hand. 
  Kim shook hands with everyone in the welcoming line as Jiang 
provided introductions. Kim obviously found some familiar faces 
and didn't forget to say, "it's been a while." 
  The South Korean leader then followed suit, introducing 
everyone accompanying him on his trip to China. 
  The welcoming ceremony lasted 15 minutes including the 
performance of national anthems and the walk down the red carpet 
between honor guards. 
  -- Kim jogged around Daiyoutai, the guest house where he is 
staying, before leaving for the welcoming ceremony and 
remembered to praise the beauty of the trees and the ponds in 
talks with Jiang. 
  Chatting before the summit opened amid a burst of camera 
flashes, Kim said he had spent a very comfortable night at the 
guest house and especially appreciated the beautiful scenery. 
  The summit room, unlike when Kim met with Japanese Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa with only one aide present, was 
filled with officials from both sides. 
  Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu, Ambassador to Beijing Hwang 
Pyong-tae, Senior Aide for Diplomacy and National Security Chong 
Chong-uk and the Foreign Ministry's Director-General for Asian 
Affairs, Yu Pyong-u, sat in for the Seoul side. 
  Foreign Minister Qian Qichen, Vice Foreign Minister Tang 
Jiaxuan, Ambassador to Seoul Zhang Tingyan and the 
Director-general for Asian Affairs at the Foreign Ministry, Wang 
Yingfan, represented Beijing. 
  -- The Kim-Jiang summit was followed by an expanded summit 
attended by 13 officials including the trade, science and 
technology and communication ministers as well as military 
leaders. 
  The two countries capped their summit with the signing of 
agreements on cultural cooperation and avoidance of double 
taxation. 

</TEXT>

