<F P=100> Near East &amp; South Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rong Yiren, Qian Qichen Meet With Libyan Foreign Minister </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2903093994 Beijing XINHUA in English 0908 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2903093994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 29 (XINHUA) -- Chinese 
Vice-President Rong Yiren met here this morning with visiting 
Libyan Foreign Minister 'Umar M. al-Muntasir. 
  Rong said that since the two countries established 
diplomatic 
relations in 1978, bilateral friendly relations of cooperation 
in various fields have developed continuously; the two countries 
share similar views on some important international issues; and 
they have cooperated well in international organizations, 
supporting each other and coordinating their steps in handling 
some issues. 
  Rong said that China is ready to make concerted efforts 
together with Libya to further strengthen such friendship and 
cooperation. 
  He expressed the conviction that al-Muntasir's visit to 
China 
will help further the friendship and cooperation between the two 
countries. 
  Al-Muntasir conveyed the compliments of the head of state of 
Libya Mu'ammar al-Qadhdhafi for the Chinese Government and 
people. 
  Al-Muntasir said that Libyan leaders are committed to 
strengthening and developing friendship and cooperation with 
China, hoping that such relations would be furthered. 
  Prior to the meeting, Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign 
Minister Qian Qichen held talks with al-Muntasir on bilateral 
relations and issues of common concern. 
  Qian said that since the establishment of diplomatic 
relations between the two countries, China and Libya have 
conducted effective cooperation in various fields, and China is 
satisfied with the development. 
  He noted that China is willing to continue to develop 
friendly relations of cooperation with Libya on the basis of the 
five principles of peaceful coexistence. 
  On Lockerbie incident, Qian said that China has all along 
been concerned with the issue. China opposes terrorism of any 
description and holds that international disputes should be 
settled through peaceful means. 
  He said that China advocates for the settlement of the 
Lockerbie crisis through consultation and negotiations by 
parties concerned. "We disapprove of imposing sanctions on 
Libya, let alone imposing severer sanctions," Qian said. 
  He pointed out that sanctions against Libya have brought 
about pains to the Libyan people and caused difficulties for 
Libya's neighboring countries and other countries concerned, 
thus intensifying the already strained regional situation. 
  He said that China understands and sympathizes with Libya 
concerning the current conditions and does not want to see the 
situation worsening. 
  He said that China appreciates the stand of Libya and the 
flexibility exhibited by it in settling the Lockerbie incident 
through peaceful negotiations. 
  Qian said that China appeals to parties concerned to take 
measures to prevent the situation from worsening and promised 
that the Chinese Government will make its due efforts to this 
end. 
  Al-Muntasir praised China for its important role in 
establishing a new world order, saying that Libya is to 
strengthen bilateral relations, coordination and cooperation in 
international affairs with China. 
  He also briefed Qian on the latest development concerning 
the 
Lockerbie incident and Libya's stand on the issue, adding that 
Libya will apply negotiations and peaceful means to resolve the 
international crisis. 
  Muntasser arrived here on March 28 at the invitation of 
Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

