<F P=100> Near East &amp; South Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   More on Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2903112094 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0911 
GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2903112094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By reporter Luo Hui (5012 6540)] </F>
  [Text] Beijing, 29 Mar (XINHUA) -- State Vice President 
Rong Yiren met here this morning with visiting Libyan Foreign 
Minister 'Umar Mustafa al-Muntasir. 
  Rong Yiren said: Since China and Libya established 
diplomatic relations in 1978, friendly relations and cooperation 
in various fields between the two countries have developed 
continuously. The two countries share similar views on some 
major international issues. They have cooperated well in 
international organizations, supporting each other and 
coordinating their efforts in handling some issues. 
  He said: China is ready to make concerted efforts with Libya 
to further strengthen friendship and cooperation in all fields. 
He expressed the conviction that al-Muntasir's visit would help 
further the friendly relations between the two countries. 
  Al-Muntasir conveyed the regards of Libyan leader Mu'ammar 
al-Qadhdhafi to the Chinese Government and people. He said: 
Libyan leaders are devoted to strengthening and developing 
friendly relations and cooperation with China, hoping that such 
relations would be furthered. 
  Prior to the meeting, Qian Qichen, vice premier of the State 
Council and foreign minister, held talks with al-Muntasir. The 
two sides exchanged views on bilateral relations and issues of 
common concern. 
  Qian Qichen said: Since they established diplomatic 
relations, China and Libya have cooperated effectively in all 
fields. China is satisfied with this development and is willing 
to continue to develop friendly relations and cooperation with 
Libya on the basis of the five principles of peaceful 
coexistence. 
  On the Lockerbie incident, Qian Qichen said: "China has 
always been concerned about this issue. China opposes terrorism 
of any description and favors the settlement of international 
disputes through peaceful means. Consistent with this stand, we 
favor the settlement of the Lockerbie crisis through 
consultation and negotiation by the parties concerned. We 
disapprove of imposing sanctions against Libya, especially of 
stepping up sanctions against that country." 
  He pointed out: Sanctions against Libya have brought 
suffering to the Libyan people and caused difficulties for 
Libya's neighbors and other countries concerned, thus escalating 
the tension in the region. China fully understands and 
sympathizes with Libya's plight and does not want to see the 
situation worsening. 
  He said: China appreciates Libya's stand on settling the 
Lockerbie incident through peaceful negotiations, as well as the 
flexibility it exhibits in this regard. China appeals to the 
parties concerned to take measures to prevent the situation from 
worsening. 
  The Chinese Government will make due efforts to this end. 
  Al-Muntasir praised China for its important role in 
establishing a new world order, saying that Libya will 
strengthen bilateral relations with China and step up 
coordination and cooperation with China in international affairs. 
  He also briefed Qian Qichen on the latest developments in 
the 
Lockerbie incident and Libya's stand on the issue, saying that 
Libya would resolve the international crisis through negotiation 
and peaceful means. 
  Al-Muntasir arrived in Beijing on 28 March at the invitation 
of Qian Qichen. 

</TEXT>

