<F P=100> Science &amp; Technology </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Program To Train Young Scientists for Next Century </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2603092194 Beijing XINHUA in English 0755 GMT 26 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2603092194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 26 (XINHUA) -- The China Academy of 
Sciences, (CAS) China's leading research body, is promoting a 
new program to strengthen the training of outstanding young 
scientists for the next century. 
  The "100-Scientist Program" will adopt public recruitment 
with the aim of selecting about 100 outstanding young scientists 
all over the country. 
  Scientists under 45 years old can apply to join the program. 
They are expected to become leading members of major research 
projects in the next century. 
  It is said that 10 to 15 such scientists will be selected 
each year for the program. 
  CAS will apply preferential treatment in research 
expenditure, housing and salaries for the program members. 
  A special leading group for the program has been set up at 
CAS. 
  The members working in state key research centers and 
laboratories will be selected from those conducting research 
into new sciences, multi-disciplinary sciences, frontier 
sciences and key projects. 
  In recent years CAS has carried out a series of training 
programs for young scientists. Now some 56 percent of 
scientists at the academy are under 45. And senior researchers 
under 45 accounted for ten percent of CAS's total. 

</TEXT>

