<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Beijing To Reform Foreign Exchange Control System </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2903054994 Beijing XINHUA in English 0436 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2903054994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 29 (XINHUA) -- China will reform its 
foreign exchange control system in an all-round way starting 
from April 1, the specialist newspaper CHINA SECURITIES reported 
today. 
  According to the paper, a national unified foreign exchange 
control market among banks will begin formal operations Friday 
[1 April]. 
  Designated foreign exchange banks are expected to replace 
enterprises in undertaking transactional activities in the 
market, which will be linked with 10 big cities. 
  An official of the State Administration of Exchange Control 
said that the establishment of the national unified market 
requires improvement. 
  At present, China has 18 banks undertaking foreign exchange 
business, and about 100 foreign-funded banks. These banks may 
apply to become members of the China foreign exchange market. 
  The official noted that China has succeeded in the 
transition 
from the old system of foreign exchange control to the new one 
over the past three months. 
  It has smoothly merged the double-track exchange rates into 
one; abolished enterprises' proportional retention of foreign 
exchange system; and carried out a bank settlement system. 
  It has also opened inter-bank foreign exchange business and 
stopped the issuing of foreign exchange certificates. 

</TEXT>

