<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Provisional' Foreign Exchange Regulations Issued </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK2903091994 Beijing CHINA DAILY in English 29 Mar 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> HK2903091994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing CHINA DAILY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Ren Kan: "Bank Trade To Centralize Most Foreign </F>
Exchange"] 
  [Text] The People's Bank of China has issued a set of 
provisional regulations on the selling, buying and payment of 
foreign exchange to ensure smooth sailing for financial reform. 
  The regulations require all foreign exchange 
receipts--except 
those held by foreign-funded enterprises and domestic 
individuals-- to be sold to designated banks. Foreign loans and 
foreign exchange for debt repayment must also be handled by the 
banks. 
  If foreign exchange is needed for import, export and other 
purposes, it can be purchased at the banks. 
  The regulations, which take effect on April 1, are aimed at 
consolidating the country's foreign exchange in the banks to 
ensure sufficient supplies for converting renmenbi under current 
accounts. 
  The official reaffirmed that the country will keep the 
foreign- exchange swap market, where foreign funded ventures can 
continue to buy and sell their foreign exchange instead of at 
the banks. 

</TEXT>

