<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Roundup' Views Foreign Investment in Yangtze River Valley </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2903085694 Beijing XINHUA in English 0819 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2903085694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Roundup: Yangtze River Valley Becomes Favorite of Foreign </F>
Investors"] 
  [Text] Shanghai, March 29 (XINHUA) -- The Chang Jiang 
river valley, boasting a strengthened economic foundation, has 
become a favorite area for foreign investment. 
  A survey shows that 130 transnational corporations have 
established 300 projects involving contractual investment 
totalling three billion U.S. dollars in Shanghai, China's 
largest economic center, and Jiangsu, Zhejiang and Hubei 
provinces. 
  Included are one quarter of the world's 100 largest 
transnational industrial corporations. 
  Shanghai has witnessed the establishment of 204 projects 
with 
a total contractual investment of 2.4 billion U.S. dollars by 
128 transnational corporations; and Jiangsu, one of China's most 
economically-developed provinces, has approved the setting up of 
60 projects funded by transnational corporations. 
  Ningbo, one of China's 14 open coastal cities in Zhejiang 
Province, and Wuhan, capital of central China's Hubei Province, 
have reported an increase in the numbers. 
  These projects funded by transnational corporations are in 
the fields of motor vehicle manufacturing, electronics and 
telecommunications, computers, biochemicals, new materials, 
precision instruments and port construction. 
  Economists here agreed that transnational corporations have 
boosted their confidence in making investment in the Chang Jiang 
river valley. 
  Robert Allen, chairman of the board of directors of the 
AT&amp;T 
company of the United States, said that China is developing 
toward a modern society and is in need of a host of advanced 
products. Therefore, his company will pursue a long-term 
investment strategy in China. 
  According to the chairman, the first project, the Shanghai 
AT&amp;T company, has become a key enterprise through four years' 
hard effort. Its products now occupy one-fourth of the market 
on the mainland. 
  According to the latest statistics, the Chang Jiang river 
valley has more than 30,000 foreign-funded projects involving 
more than 35 billion U.S. dollars, accounting for one-fourth of 
the total foreign investment on the Chinese mainland. 
  So far over 10,000 projects have gone into operation, and 80 
percent of them are profitable. 
  Investments made by transnational corporations in the Chang 
Jiang river valley are concentrated on pillar industries, 
infrastructure facilities, real estate, tourism facilities and 
the land development by large tracts. 
  At present, a number of Hong Kong companies are cooperating 
with Shanghai in improving its urban transport facilities and 
constructing a commercial center. 
  The Shanghai municipal government plans to open more markets 
and construction of infrastructure facilities including a power 
plant, a subway and an airport to attract foreign investment, 
from transnational corporations in particular, this year. 
  Construction of the Suzhou Industrial Park, a 
Singapore-Chinese joint venture, is proceeding smoothly. 
  The largest Sino-foreign project in Jiangsu Province, the 
industrial park, which covers 70 square kilometers, is receiving 
streams of overseas investors. 
  So far the park has concluded cooperative contracts on more 
than 50 projects with a sum of three billion U.S. dollars on 
contract. 
  The projects are in the electronics, machinery, textiles, 
and 
tourism industries. 
  Port construction in Shanghai, Nanjing, Lusi, Ningbo and 
Wuhan along the Chang Jiang river has attracted strong 
investment from Hong Kong. 
  According to some investors, the Chang Jiang river valley, 
in 
particular the Chang Jiang river delta consisting of Shanghai, 
Jiangsu and Zhejiang, has been provided with a better economic 
foundation, talented people and improved infrastructure 
facilities. 
  The densely populated area will offer conditions and market 
for foreign-funded enterprises to prosper. 

</TEXT>

