<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mainland Vessels To Be Confiscated if Detained Twice </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2903043494 Taipei China Broadcasting Corporation News 
Network in Mandarin 2300 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2903043494 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei China Broadcasting Corporation News 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Mandarin </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Hookup" program] </F>
  [Text] The Mainland Affairs Council [MAC] held a plenary 
meeting on 28 March. The meeting adopted the division of work 
in handling the unauthorized entry of mainland vessels into 
[words indistinct] Tung-sha and Nan-sha waters. The MAC decided 
in principle that it is necessary to fire warning shots to drive 
away any mainland vessels which enter without permission our 
country's restricted water areas. If they enter prohibited 
water areas, they shall be driven away with gunfire without 
warning. However, if they refuse to leave, both the vessels and 
the personnel on board shall be taken into custody. If a vessel 
is taken into custody twice, it shall be confiscated. 
  Kao Kung-lien, vice chairman of the MAC, said: [Begin 
recording] The detention shall be recorded into the ship's 
data. According Article 32 of the (?Cross-Strait) Regulations 
[liang an tiao li], a vessel shall be confiscated if it is 
detained twice. [end recording] 
  On the handling of smuggled goods, the MAC meeting decided: 
Smuggled tobacco, wine, and other ordinary goods shall be 
confiscated. Smuggled farm products shall be handled by the 
local county government on behalf of the Council of Agriculture. 

</TEXT>

