<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Navy Takes Delivery of Second Missile Frigate </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2803134294 Taipei CNA in English 1245 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2803134294 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Benjamin Yeh] </F>
  [Text] Kaohsiung, March 28 (CNA) -- The Republic of China 
[ROC] Navy on Monday [28 March] took delivery of the second of 
the eight missile frigates it has ordered from the China 
Shipbuilding Corp. 
  The ceremony, presided over by Vice President Li Yuan-zu on 
behalf of President Li Teng-hui was witnessed by more than 100 
guests, including National Defense Minister Sun Chen and Admiral 
Liu Ho-chien, chief of the general staff. 
  "The purpose of strengthening our military power is for 
defense, not offense. It is for sustaining peace, not for 
provoking war," Li said. 
  Construction of the warship, named "Cheng Ho" after a noted 
Ching dynasty admiral, began on Dec. 21, 1990. 
  The first frigate went into service last May and the last 
one 
is scheduled to begin service by October 1999. 
  The eight 4,200-ton frigates, which will eventually cost the 
Navy more than NT [new Taiwan] $40 billion (US$1.5 billion), are 
to replace part of the Navy's aging fleet. According to the 
International Institute for Strategic Studies, the ROC Navy had 
24 destroyers and nine frigates as of the end of 1992. 
  Taiwan also agreed on a US$4.8 billion deal in 1991 to buy 
16 
Lafayette-class frigates from France. 
  With a maximum speed of 27.5 nautical miles per hour, each 
of 
the frigates will be armed with locally-manufactured Hsiung-feng 
ship- to-ship missiles, US standard ship-to-air missiles, anti 
submarine torpedoes, and a Phalanx weapons system built by the 
General Dynamics Corp. of the United States. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

