<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trade Circles `Angered' Over Low Product Quality Rating </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2603091594 Taipei CNA in English 0719 GMT 26 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2603091594 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Christiaan Virant] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, March 26 (CNA) -- A recent Gallup Poll of 
world consumers that rates Taiwan products below those of 
Mainland China in quality has angered business executives and 
trade officials here. 
  The poll found that respondents believed products from the 
United States, Japan and Germany topped other countries in terms 
of product quality, followed by Mainland China, Taiwan and 
Central American nations. 
  "This rating flies in the face of international praise for 
Taiwan products," Stan Shih, chairman of the Brand International 
Promotion Association told reporters after reading the poll 
results. 
  Shih said the poll was conducted by the US-based Gallup 
Organization and divided responses into three areas, North 
America, South America and the rest of the world. 
  The arbitrary division may have influenced the survey 
outcome, Shih said. 
  "Those surveyed from countries with poor educational 
standards may have confused Taiwan with Thailand or thought of 
Taiwan as part of Mainland China," he added. 
  Secretary-General Huang Hsing-kuo of the private Foreign 
Trade Association explained that the low product quality rating 
also may have resulted from a high number of survey responses 
from India and Latin America. 
  "Taiwan product promotion efforts target the US and Europe 
and not other areas of the globe," Huang explained. 
  "As a result, Americans and Europeans are well aware that 
Taiwan products are of the highest quality, but people from 
other countries may not know this," he added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

