<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Expert' Rules Out Beijing Military Attack Before 2000 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2603091694 Taipei CNA in English 0737 GMT 26 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2603091694 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Debbie Kuo] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, March 26 (CNA) -- The Communist Chinese 
military will not attack Taiwan before the year 2000, a military 
expert said Saturday [26 March]. 
  However, Taiwan will be at an increased risk of attack 
during 
the years 2001 to 2010, Niu Hsien-chung, a military strategist 
and author of several war game books told legislators at a 
public hearing on security issues. 
  Beijing will be preoccupied with resolving thorny problems 
related to the retrocession of Hong Kong and Macao until the 
turn of the century, ruling out the possibility of any attack on 
Taiwan, Niu said. 
  Niu was at the Legislative Yuan to comment on the recently 
published Ministry of National Defense White Paper. 
  Niu said that the white paper lists six reasons and ways for 
a communist offensive against Taiwan, but did not discuss when 
such attacks would take place. 
  "Timing is vitally important," he said. 
  On the ministry's plan to size down the armed forces to 
about 
400,000 in 10 years, Niu said if the plan is a must, it should 
be carried out in five years rather than 10. 
  He added that the White Paper only dealt with military 
maneuvers against Taiwan. "As a matter of fact," he said, 
"non-military attacks would be even more deadly." 
  The white paper claims that the foremost event which might 
trigger a military attack from Beijing would be a declaration of 
independence by Taiwan. 
  Other major events include internal large-scale chaos or 
riots within Taiwan, foreign intervention in the internal 
affairs of Taiwan, refusal to hold reunification talks with the 
mainland, the development of nuclear arms on the island, and 
political instability in the post-Deng Xiaoping era, which might 
lead to a communist attack on the island. 
  According to the white paper, some of the six ways the 
mainland could possibly attack Taiwan include a sudden missile 
offensive against targets on Taiwan's western coast or seizing 
upon fishing disputes to trick Taiwan's Navy into a maritime 
confrontation. 
  The communists may lure Taiwan air and naval forces into 
battle after first attacking Taiwan-held offshore islands. 
Mainland forces could also launch a rapid-fire invasion and 
take over Taiwan-held islands, the white paper said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

