<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   CNA on `Step Forward' Toward GATT Membership </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2603092294 Taipei CNA in English 0747 GMT 26 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2603092294 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By M. J. Tzou and Sofia Wu] </F>
  [Text] Geneva, March 25 (CNA) -- Taiwan has taken a step 
forward in its bid to join the General Agreement on Tariffs and 
Trade (GATT), a Taiwan delegate said here Friday [25 March] 
after wrapping up bilateral tariff reduction talks with six 
countries. 
  Director-General Huang Yen-chao of the Board of Foreign 
Trade 
told a group of Taiwan reporters that all the six countries -- 
Hungary, South Africa, Chile, Turkey, New Zealand and Australia 
-- have reaffirmed their support for Taiwan's GATT entry during 
the tariff reduction talks. 
  Huang, who arrived in Geneva March 20 at the head of a 
14-member delegation for the first-round tariff talks with the 
six countries in connection with Taiwan's GATT bid, said the 
talks proceeded smoothly. 
  "Nevertheless, all of the six countries have asked US to 
remove tariff and non-tariff trade barriers in accordance with 
GATT requirements," Huang noted. 
  They were particularly concerned with Taiwan's quota and 
area 
restrictions on farm trade and some industrial products, such as 
compact cars, Huang said. 
  "We must accelerate trade liberalization and adjust our 
agricultural development strategies in order to facilitate our 
GATT bid," Huang added. 
  Taiwan will hold further bilateral or multilateral tariff 
talks with the six countries later this year. Taiwan already 
held informal bilateral tariff reduction talks with the United 
States, and more than 10 other countries have requested similar 
talks with Taiwan. 
  Taiwan was admitted as a GATT observer in September 1992 and 
is expected to become a full member by the end of this year. 
Huang, who is leaving here for home Sunday, said he will return 
to Geneva in May to attend a meeting of the GATT working party 
screening Taiwan's GATT application. 

</TEXT>

