<F P=102>  OW2803134094 Taipei CNA in English 1248 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2803134094 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Benjamin Yeh] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, March 28 (CNA) -- The Republic of China 
[ROC] and the Central African Republic on Monday [28 March] 
signed a joint communique pledging to step up bilateral friendly 
relations. 
  Foreign Affairs Minister Chien Fu and his Central African 
Republic Counterpart Simon Bedava-Ngaro signed the communique on 
behalf of their countries. 
  The deal came at the close of the first meeting of the mixed 
commission comprising officials from both countries. 
  Topics discussed during the six days of talks were economic 
and technical cooperation, transportation issues facing the 
African country, cooperation in rural development, medical and 
educational cooperation, and mining cooperation. 
  Chien told the press that Bedaya-Ngaro had reiterated his 
country's full support of the ROC's bid to join the United 
Nations. 
  The commission will meet in the Central African Republic 
next 
year. 
  While here, Bedaya-Ngaro called on President Li Teng-hui and 
Premier Lien Chan. 

