<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Changes to New Territories Land Regulations </TI></H3>
<H4>   XINHUA Official Comments </H4>
<F P=102> OW2603132694 Beijing XINHUA in English 1251 GMT 26 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2603132694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hong Kong, March 26 (XINHUA) -- The British Hong 
Kong Government, by supporting amendments to the law governing 
indigenous inheritance right in the New Territories, contravenes 
the Sino- British Joint Declaration and the Basic Law, said a 
Hong Kong-based Chinese official. 
  Zhu Yucheng, deputy director of the XINHUA NEWS AGENCY Hong 
Kong branch, made the remarks Friday [25 March] in response to 
reporters' questions about the amendment to the New Territories 
Land (Exemption) Bill, which was proposed by a legislator and 
supported by the Hong Kong Government. 
  Since the law amendment is an important matter straddling 
the 
1997 handover, Zhu said, consultations between China and Britain 
are necessary according to the Sino-British Joint Declaration. 
  As for the traditional interests and rights of the New 
Territories inhabitants, Zhu said the Basic Law of the future 
special administrative regions has specific stipulations. 
  Article 40 of the Basic Law says that "the lawful 
traditional 
rights and interests of the indigenous inhabitants of the `New 
Territories' shall be protected by the Hong Kong Special 
Administrative Region." 
  Article 122 says that "in the case of old schedule lots, 
village lots, small houses and similar rural holdings, where the 
property was on 30 June 1984 held by, or, in the case of small 
houses granted after that date, where the property is granted 
to, a lessee descended through the male line from a person who 
was in 1898 a resident of an established village in Hong Kong, 
the previous rent shall remain unchanged so long as the property 
is held by that lessee or by one of his lawful successors in the 
male line." 
  Zhu pointed out that the Legislative Council, an advisory 
body of the Hong Kong British authorities, has no right to make 
law amendment. 
  He criticized some people for trying to cause divisions and 
confrontation among the Hong Kong people and sabotage social 
stability in the territory by taking advantage of the amendment. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

