<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Former Civil Servants Reject Adviser Positions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK2703020894 Hong Kong EASTERN EXPRESS in English 26 Mar 94 
p 2 </F>

<F P=103> HK2703020894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong EASTERN EXPRESS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Rain Ren] </F>
  [Text] The former secretary for education and man-power, 
John Chan, and the former secretary for treasury, Yeung Kai-yin, 
confirmed yesterday they had turned down invitations to join 
Beijing's third batch of Hong Kong affairs advisers. About 50 
more Hong Kong affairs advisers will be appointed in Beijing 
after the Easter holiday next month, a Chinese government 
official said. 
  Chan said the Chinese had approached him in an informal way, 
indicating their intention of inviting him to join the body. 
This was to avoid embarrassment had an official invitation been 
turned down. Chan told the Chinese that he preferred not to 
accept an offer, saying it was a personal decision. "I don't 
think I need to explain why," he said. Chan left the civil 
service last June after a 27-year career to become managing 
director of Kowloon Motor Bus. 
  Yeung, who also resigned last year, gave the same reason for 
not accepting Beijing's offer. "I've made it public that if I 
am asked either by the Chinese government or the Hong Kong 
government to give my personal views on any matters to the 
extent possible, I will do so if I can without taking any 
further position," Yeung said. "I don't need any title." 
  A locally-based Chinese official refused to confirm Chan and 
Yeung's rejection but said it was a matter for individuals 
whether to accept. China has invited several former civil 
servants to be advisers, including Sir David Akers-Jones, the 
former chief secretary, and Wong Ying-wai, the former 
administrative officer. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

