<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Survey Shows Lack of Interest in Civil Service Careers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK2703021294 Hong Kong EASTERN EXPRESS in English 26 Mar 94 
p 3 </F>

<F P=103> HK2703021294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong EASTERN EXPRESS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Billy Adams] </F>
  [Text] Who wants to be a civil servant? Not Hong Kong's 
young people, it seems, who quake at the thought of a job in 
government. No challenge, no prospects, they claim. With 
rumours rife of a mass exodus from the ranks in the run-up to 
1997, more than a few eyebrows in Government House are bound to 
be raised by a survey suggesting there will not be many willing 
to fill the void. 
  The Secretary for the Civil Service, Michael Sze, told 
legislators on Thursday there was sufficient existing talent who 
could be promoted to fill vacant senior posts. But a poll of 
513 people between the ages of 15 and 29 showed more than half 
had no intention of applying to join the civil service. Only 30 
per cent wanted to join, the survey conducted by the Hong Kong 
Federation of Youth Groups showed. "The poll indicates that a 
smooth transition is still of great concern to the young people 
in the run-up to 1997," a spokesman said. 

</TEXT>

