<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Changes to New Territories Land Regulations </TI></H3>
<H4>   PRC Spokesman Comments </H4>
<F P=102> OW2903120294 Beijing XINHUA in English 1144 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2903120294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 29 (XINHUA) -- The traditional lawful 
rights of the original residents in the New Territories in Hong 
Kong must be protected and not be revised at will, a spokesman 
said here today. 
  A spokesman for the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office under 
the State Council made this statement when asked about the 
revisions presumptuously agreed by the Hong Kong authorities on 
the draft immunity regulation on land in the new territories. 
The revisions have caused strong protests from original local 
residents. 
  The spokesman pointed out that the concept of "original 
residents in the New Territories" and the lawful rights of 
original residents, which were written into the Joint 
Declaration and the Basic Law, should not be removed. 
  The Hong Kong authorities should take the protests of the 
residents into consideration and handle the issue properly 
through full consultation with the original local residents in 
accordance with the Basic Law, thus avoiding man-made social 
instability and separation, he said. 
  The spokesman noted that the British authorities had 
announced in 1898 that all land in the New Territories belonged 
to the British royal house following its forced lease of the 
land through unequal treaties, depriving original residents of 
the New Territories of their land-owning rights. 
  That announcement was persistently resisted by local 
residents. As a result, the later draft immunity regulations on 
land in the New Territories ruled that farmland owners need only 
hand in nominal rents. 
  Annex III to the Sino-British Joint Declaration rules that 
the rent on rural land leased by original residents in the New 
Territories "shall remain unchanged so long as the property is 
held by that person (one who was in 1898 a resident of an 
established village in Hong Kong) or by one of his lawful 
successors in the male line." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

