<F P=101> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jiang Zemin Says China Not To Become Military Threat </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1503233694 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 15 Mar 
94 Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1503233694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Moriyasu Okazaki] </F>
  [Text] Beijing, 14 Mar -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin 
met with Susumu Nikaido, former vice president of the Liberal 
Democratic Party who is now visiting China, in Beijing on 14 
March. During this meeting, Jiang emphatically repeated: "Even 
if China continues to grow and becomes powerful in the future, 
it will never become a military threat." He thus refuted 
growing warnings by China's neighbors, who are now alarmed by 
its sharp increase in military spending, that the country will 
become a threat to them. Jiang also indicated he was looking 
forward to Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's visit to China 
starting on 19 March, and said: "I want to discuss various 
issues with Prime Minister Hosokawa, too." 

</TEXT>

