<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Says Russia To Provide Aid if DPRK Invaded </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3003032394 Beijing XINHUA in English 0300 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3003032394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Russia To Provide Aid If DPRK Invaded" -- XINHUA headline] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, March 29 (XINHUA) -- Russian Deputy Foreign 
Minister Aleksandr Panov said here today that Russia would 
provide aid to the Democratic People's Republic of Korea if the 
latter is invaded without any provocation. 
  Speaking at a press conference, Panov said that the 
agreements signed by the former Soviet Union and DPRK are still 
effective, but Russia will make decisions on the basis of its 
own analysis. 
  Panov also briefed reporters on Russia's new proposal for 
solving the crisis in the Korean peninsula. 
  According to Panov, the situation on the Korean peninsula is 
so tense that it is on the verge of war. He suggested that an 
international conference be held among China, the United States, 
Japan, Russia, DPRK, the Republic of Korea, as well as the 
United Nations and the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA). 
  He said that such a conference should first of all discuss 
how to guarantee the non-nuclear status of the Korean peninsula 
including the joint announcement on a nuclear-free Korean 
peninsula by both sides of Korea. 
  Panov suggested the international conference be held first 
in 
Geneva and then in Pyongyang and Seoul in turn. 
  He said the United Nations and IAEA have made great efforts 
to solve the Korean issue, but the results are not always 
satisfactory. 
  He added that all related parties are considering Russia's 
new proposal. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

