<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Li Peng Meets Outgoing, Newly-Appointed Foreign Ambassadors </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2903154694 Beijing XINHUA in English 1501 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2903154694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 29 (XINHUA) -- Chinese Premier Li 
Peng met with two out-going and six newly-appointed foreign 
ambassadors to China here this afternoon. 
  The two out-going ones were: Italian Ambassador Oliviero 
Rossi and Chilean Ambassador Eduardo Bravo Woodhouse. 
  The six newly-appointed ambassadors were: Mustafizur Rahman, 
of Bangladesh, Sawanit Khongsiri, of Thailand, Sverre Bergh 
Johansen, of Norway, Juwana, of Indonesia, Bassam Kubbah, of 
Iraq, and Victor J. Gauci, of Malta. 
  During the meeting, the Chinese premier briefed the 
ambassadors on China's domestic situation, saying that to 
develop the national economy was the central job for China. The 
whole country, with one heart, was now concentrating on 
accomplishing the tasks set by the newly concluded second 
session of China's 8th National People's Congress. 
  Premier Li said that China needs a peaceful international 
environment, and it is willing to develop cooperative relations 
of mutual benefit with all friendly nations. 
  Li expressed his thanks to the two out-going ambassadors for 
their efforts in promoting China's relations with their 
respective countries during their terms, and he hoped after they 
return home, they would continue to contribute to the 
development of such relations. 
  The Chinese premier said that he hoped that the new 
ambassadors will, in their terms, make efforts for the promotion 
of relations in various fields between China and their own 
nations, and that he is expecting to see a sustained development 
of such relations. 

</TEXT>

