<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sino-U.S. Joint Venture Set Up To Develop CAD/CAM Software </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2903140094 Beijing XINHUA in English 1346 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2903140094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 29 (XINHUA) -- CV Technology Co. 
Ltd., a joint venture between China Aerospace Corporation and 
the Computervision Corporation (CV) of the United States, was 
set up here today. 
  Song Jian, Chinese state councillor and minister in charge 
of 
the State Science and Technology Commission, met here today with 
Russel E. Planitzer, chairman and chief executive of the CV 
Corporation, who came here to attend the inauguration ceremony 
of the joint venture. 
  The newly-established joint venture will concentrate on the 
development of software for computer-aided design (CAD) and 
computer aided manufacture (CAM), and sell the products both in 
China and in the international market. 
  Liu Jiyuan, general manager of China Aerospace Corporation, 
said that more than ten years ago China's aerospace industry 
began to introduce CAD and CAM software from the CV Corporation 
for researching and manufacturing various rockets and 
satellites, with fairly fruitful results. 
  Now China Aerospace Corporation has made computer 
application 
as one of the three pillar industries producing civil products 
with aerospace science and technology, and the corporation will 
further expand foreign economic and technological cooperation 
and exchange in this field, Liu added. 
  Sources said that the CV Corporation is a world-renowned 
software producer, with a history of 25 years. Last year it had 
a total sales income of 800 million U.S. dollars, some 18 
percent of the world's machinery engineering software market. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

