<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Syrian Paper on U.S. Secretary's Upcoming Tour </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2903132294 Beijing XINHUA in English 1255 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2903132294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Damascus, March 29 (XINHUA) -- U.S. Secretary of 
State Warren Christopher will make a fresh tour of the Middle 
East in the second half of April before the resumption of the 
Arab-Israel bilateral peace talks in Washington, a Syrian 
newspaper reported today. 
  The newspaper "AL-BA'ATH," mouthpiece of the ruling party, 
called today on the U.S., a co-sponsor of the Middle East peace 
process, to play its supposed role for achieving the objectives 
of this process. 
  The paper argued that the U.S. is capable of putting 
pressure 
on Israel to commit itself to adhering to the peace process in 
both words and deeds. 
  The Arab parties involved in the peace talks include Syria, 
Jordan, Lebanon and the Palestinians. 
  According to diplomatic sources in the Syrian capital, 
Christopher's coming tour of the region is intended to hold 
preliminary talks with the parties involved in the Middle East 
peace process to remove the obstacles to the resumption of the 
peace negotiations and set a date for such resumption. 
  Arab political sources in Damascus maintain that Christopher 
is likely to make some progress on the Palestinian-Israeli track 
of the peace negotiations, which will enable him to focus on 
pushing the peace process forward. 
  Yet the sources hold that Christopher's task of persuading 
the Arab parties, particularly Syria, to resume the Washington 
talks would not be an easy job because Syria adheres to its 
consistent stand. Syria insists that peace can be achieved only 
on the basis of a complete Israeli withdrawal from the occupied 
Arab territories and the full restoration of the Palestinian 
people's rights, especially their rights to repatriation, 
self-determination and the establishment of an independent state. 
  The sources add that Syria adheres to the peace-for-land 
principle and condemns Israel's intransigent stand which 
consists in its insistence on considering the security 
arrangements to be made in the Golan Heights without showing 
willingness to withdraw completely from there. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

