<F P=100> Northwest Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shaanxi-Gansu-Ningxia Basin Rich in Water Resources </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2503071894 Beijing XINHUA in English 0628 GMT 25 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2503071894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Xian, March 25 (XINHUA) -- Chinese scientists say 
that northwest China's Shaanxi-Gansu-Ningxia Basin, despite its 
vast area of dry land, is holding rich water resources. 
  A research team, headed by senior geologist Huang Zhongxin, 
under the Changqing oil-prospecting administration of the basin 
came to the conclusion based on a systematic study of a large 
amount of hydrogeological materials and other related 
information amassed over the past four decades. 
  According to them, the basin has a water-bearing area of 
144,000 sq [square] km, with total reserves of 11,400 billion cu 
m [cubic meters], of which, 6,960 billion cu m are fresh water. 
This is equivalent to 267 times the volume of China's largest 
freshwater lake, Poyang Lake, in east China's Jiangxi Province. 
  Most of the water-bearing strata lie 500 m to 600 m below 
the 
surface, but some of them, especially in Shaanxi Province, are 
no more than 100 m below the surface. 
  The scientists believe that the development of such rich 
water resources will not affect oil and natural gas prospecting 
work in the basin. 
  They add that the exploration of the water resources will 
play an important role in helping solve the problem of 
industrial and drinking water supply and underground flooding of 
oilfields in the area. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

