<H3> <TI>   Comments on Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3003134594 Beijing XINHUA in English 1304 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3003134594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 30 (XINHUA) -- South Korean President 
Kim Yong-sam said here today that he had fruitful discussions 
with Japanese and Chinese leaders on ways to ensure stability 
and prosperity in Northeast Asia. 
  And he said that he believes the tour has provided the 
momentum to unfold a new age for the Asia-Pacific region with 
South Korea, Japan and China walking hand in hand. 
  Kim explained that in discussions with Japan's Prime 
Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa he had explored ways to further promote mutual 
cooperation, and in China he had shared with President Jiang 
Zemin the view that peace and stability on the Korean peninsula 
are essential to maintain that state for the whole of Northeast 
Asia. 
  He added that South Korea and China have an identical view 
on 
the realization of peace and stability on the Korean peninsula 
and that the two countries will cooperate closely in resolving 
the nuclear dispute over site inspections with the Democratic 
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK). 
  He said he believed that his visit to China has laid a solid 
foundation for strengthening economic cooperation between the 
two countries. 
  Kim paid a state visit to China from March 26 to 30 after 
his 
three-day visit to Japan, his first visit to China since he 
assumed office in February last year. 

</TEXT>

