<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Columnist Says Beijing's Role in Korean Crisis `Limited' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK3003055294 Hong Kong TA KUNG PAO in Chinese 30 Mar 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> HK3003055294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong TA KUNG PAO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Political Talk" column by Shih Chun-yu (2457 0689 3768): </F>
"Korean Peninsula Needs Peace and Stability"] 
  [Text] The visit of ROK President Kim Yong-sam to China is 
an important event in the relations between the two countries. 
Both countries are ancient countries, and traditional relations 
go back several thousands years. After the war, for various 
reasons, the two countries discontinued exchanges for a long 
period and official diplomatic relations were only established 
recently. In recent years, with the common efforts of both 
sides, PRC-ROK relations have developed rapidly and the scope of 
exchanges and cooperation has become more and more extensive. 
China has become the third biggest trading partner of the ROK, 
and the ROK is also the sixth biggest trading partner for China. 
Last year, the volume of trade between the two countries 
amounted to $11 billion. ROK investment in China is nearly $1 
billion. China is one of the countries in which the ROK has 
made the greatest investment. All this has laid a very good 
foundation for further developing friendly relations and 
mutually beneficial economic cooperation between the two 
countries. Friendship and cooperation between China and the ROK 
are conducive to the stability of the Asia-Pacific region and to 
world peace. 
<H5>  Crisis Can Only Be Resolved Through Talks </H5>
  President Kim Yong-sam has come to China at a time when the 
situation on the Korean peninsula is extremely tense, and the 
stances of the two countries on resolving the crisis on the 
Korean peninsula has naturally attracted the world's attention. 
Chinese leaders have clearly pointed out that the Chinese 
Government sincerely hopes that the Korean peninsula can 
maintain long-term peace and stability and that they support the 
idea of the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula. China 
does not favor the deployment, production, or research of any 
nuclear weapons either on the northern or southern side of the 
Korean peninsula. China holds that without peace and stability 
on the Korean peninsula, there cannot be real peace and 
stability in the Asia-Pacific region. The controversial nuclear 
issue on the Korean peninsula at present should be appropriately 
resolved through dialogue between the DPRK, the ROK, the United 
States, and the International Atomic Energy Agency. In 
addition, this kind of dialogue requires patience. 
  For some time, many countries have issued appeals hoping 
that 
China can play a part in resolving the nuclear issue on the 
Korean peninsula. President Kim Yong-sam has expressed the same 
hope. This is understandable because China and the DPRK are 
close neighbors and the two countries have maintained friendly 
relations of cooperation. China has indeed made energetic 
efforts to do what she can in this respect. However, China and 
the DPRK are two independent sovereign countries after all. 
China does not have any nuclear cooperation with the DPRK. How 
to deal with and handle the nuclear issue can only be analyzed, 
assessed, and decided by the DPRK herself. Therefore, China's 
role is limited. 
<H5>  Threats Are Futile </H5>
  For the sake of peace and stability on the Korean peninsula 
and to create a favorable atmosphere for dialogue and talks, 
China is opposed to displays of force and the use of threats. 
People are aware that the sudden emergence of a tense situation 
on the Korean peninsula is entirely the result of some 
countries' vain attempts to exert pressure. The United States 
has announced the dispatch of "Patriot" missiles to the ROK, 
Japan wanted to draw up "economic sanctions" against the DPRK, 
and the ROK announced a "special state of alert" for the three 
armed services of the Army, the Navy, and the Air Force. Under 
such circumstances, threatening words from both sides have also 
gradually escalated. The DPRK side has said that if war breaks 
out, Seoul will become "a sea of fire," and the ROK side 
asserted that it would "take advantage of the opportunity of the 
north's provocation to reunify the entire peninsula." This can 
only aggravate confrontation between the two sides. 
  What is gratifying is that during recent talks with Chinese 
leaders, President Kim Yong-sam said that "the ROK also hopes to 
settle the nuclear issue through dialogue and talks and does not 
wish to exert pressure." At the same time, according to 
information from the DPRK side, "the DPRK is ready to accept a 
new round of investigations by people from abroad of her nuclear 
facilities." These are undoubtedly positive developments in the 
state of affairs and a step in the right direction. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

