<F P=100> Science &amp; Technology </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Announces Production of Man-Made Diamonds </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2903133094 Beijing XINHUA in English 1115 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2903133094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 29 (XINHUA) -- Following a Russian 
breakthrough, China has now become the second country capable of 
producing man-made polycrystal diamonds, the Ministry of Geology 
and Mineral Resources (MGMR) announced here today. 
  Thin-wall drilling bits and geological core-extracting 
drilling bits made of this material have proved more efficient 
and long- lasting than earlier types. 
  China produced monocrystal diamonds in 1963 and afterwards 
took steps toward creating polycrystal ones, the MGMR said. 
  In 1991, the project to develop polycrystal diamonds was 
listed as a major scientific project in the nation's Eighth 
Five-Year Plan. 
  Diamonds are widely used in the fields of aviation and space 
flight, machine processing, national defense science and 
geological drilling. 
  Possession of diamonds has always been considered an 
important factor in judging the industrialization of a country, 
according to an official from the MGMR. 
  Natural diamonds are rare worldwide, with an annual output 
of 
400 million carats. The natural polycrystal diamond has only 
been produced in Brazil, and it holds a value ten times that of 
the monocrystal variety. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-4466 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi061_m_94002" </HT>


